This case has not been concluded. Unless a judgment of conviction is entered, the defendant is presumed innocent of all charges.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

2:55 PM Defendant Keimon Dantrell Joiner in court, in custody.  Attorney Joel N Urmanski in court for State of Wisconsin. 
Attorney Barbara J Kirchner in court as standby counsel for today.
Court notes that Deft exercised his right to an Attorney and exercised his right to have a Preliminary Hearing within 10 days. Public Defender's Office was not able to appoint within 10 days. Court appointed Atty Kirchner as standby counsel for today.
Deft submitted Waiver of Right to Attorney for today's Preliminary Hearing and Motion to Dismiss only, will not continue throughout the case.
Court finds valid Waiver of Right to Attorney for today.
Defendant filed Motion to Dismiss citing defective Complaint. 
State notes caselaw State vs. Bembenek and makes argument, requesting Court object to Motion on both Counts.
Atty Kirchner reads list of reasons that Deft and Atty Kirchner came up with as to why the complaint is defective.
Court notes State vs. Adams and State vs. Maxwell and notes reasonable inferences and facts are sufficient.
Court denies Motion to Dismiss.
Officer Taylor, in person, sworn and testified - D, X
Witness ID's Deft in courtroom. 
Deft objects to identification, Court over rules and Deft is identified.
State rests and requests bindover.
Defendant does not have any witnesses.
Court finds probable cause/Deft bound over.
Defendant requests Arraignment at a later date.
State amended Count 2 to Obstructing an Officer.
Information emailed to Clerk and printed for Deft.
Court authorizes Atty Kirchner to remain on the case as standby counsel until the Public Defender has appointed.
State notes with standby counsel the Discovery will be provided directly to Defendant due to ethical rules. 
Court orders the bills to be sent to Public Defender's Office due to Deft qualifying.
